How strong and viable is the current society of mortals according to Musk? Humanity has already developed to the point of creating garbage islands in the ocean, microplastics in everyone's bloodstream with unknown health consequences, and various other interesting and diverse methods of destroying the habitat and consuming non-renewable resources. Yet, we continue to increase military budgets. What will happen next, what kind of Earth will our descendants inherit? But who, except for a few crazies, cares ‚Äì we live only once, and we need to grab our share and take everything from life; there won't be another chance to live well. Only a society of immortals will have the genuine motivation to preserve the environment and conserve resources.

And what does it mean to eliminate death? I don't think anyone in an immortal society will be forbidden from ending their own life when they're tired of it. I'm sure there will be those who do. But those who don't want to die should have that opportunity.

It is a logical error to assume that society as it is could just become immortal while not changing in any other way.

Life extension by itself won't eradicate death - there are many other causes and risks. But life extension will be a key step for humanity to value life more, and to evolve in a way to make death risks (or personality loss risks, if we learn some uploading thing so that biological death won't be a problem) as low as possible. It can probably take much time to build the society without death, and it will differ from our society probably more than we from Neanderthals. Think of strong AI everywhere, intelligence amplification/augmentation (IA), mind uploading, etc etc.

And life extension is what we need now at the society level, for multiple reasons:
1. Balance the demographics - in a way that works, based on the natural human desire to live, not forcing people to reproduce or "replacing" those who don't with those who do.
2. Economy (Longevity Dividend) - keeping millions of skilled people alive and working for longer. "Replacing" them with children costs lots of money, time and could be actually impossible at the macro scale.
3. Environmental care - we need people to be more long-term motivated for sustainability, less for short-term overconsumption (often stimulated by "carpe diem" or "in 100 years you'll be dead anyway" mindset).
4. Social improvement - with increasing technological abilities and economic challenges, people just need more time to learn (including learning how to coexist, and having more motivation for good - just like with the environment).
5. Long-term scientific projects, including space flights. Space is big and takes time, months even to Mars, the closest planet. Interstellar flight won't be possible at all for people with animal lifespans (and probably also with animal non-upgraded bodies).

So if you are serious into space, you cannot be not serious into time, i. e. life extension.
